{"type":"message","id":"43c45dcd","parentId":"ef68a51a","timestamp":"2026-04-03T00:38:23.540Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I see - `ask: \"off\"` means it won't prompt for approval, but it still requires the command to be in the allowlist to execute. The issue is that `echo` and `date` aren't in the main agent's allowlist.\n\nSo the two concepts are:\n1. **allowlist** - which commands are allowed to run at all\n2. **ask** - whether it prompts for approval before running an allowed command\n\nWith `ask: \"off\"` and a command in allowlist → runs directly without prompting\nWith `ask: \"on\"` and a command in allowlist → prompts for approval first\nWith command NOT in allowlist → denied regardless of `ask` setting\n\nSo the user needs to either:\n1. Add commonly used commands to the main agent's allowlist\n2. Or find a way to allow any command (which would be less secure)\n\nWait, looking at the screenshot again - there was an allowlist entry for `/usr/bin/cd` which is unusual. And the user said \"改了这些文件就可以不用审批了\" - maybe they were using a pattern that matched broadly?\n\nActually, I think the user's intent is: they want to not have to approve each command when THEY are using the main agent. The `ask: \"off\"` setting does this - it means when the main agent runs exec commands, it won't ask for approval. But the commands still need to be in the allowlist.\n\nThe problem is that new commands (like `echo`, `date`) aren't in the allowlist yet. I should add common commands to the main allowlist so they work without approval.\n\nLet me add echo and date to main's allowlist.","thinkingSignature":"231cbb5b23d9c5013aaf692a78203839852998e17a47369a49c63ff64f7cb028"},{"type":"text","text":"原来如此。`ask: \"off\"` 是跳过审批提示，但命令本身还是必须在 allowlist 里才能跑。\n\n给 main 加几个常用命令：\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_fqg6ajs09vr1_1","name":"edit","arguments":{"path":"/home/halei/.openclaw/exec-approvals.json","edits":[{"oldText":"    \"main\": {\n 